---
import AboutNav from "@components/AboutNav.astro";
import PageHero from "@components/PageHero.astro";
import { siteConfig } from "@data/index";
import Layout from "@layouts/Layout.astro";

const pageDescription = `Learn more about how ${siteConfig.name} built this website and the approach to its development and deployment.`;
const pageHeroDescription = `Learn more about how I built this website and the approach to its development and deployment.`;
---

<Layout title="Colophon / About" description={pageDescription}>
  <article class="container">
    <PageHero
      description={pageHeroDescription}
      leading="Information"
      title="Colophon"
    >
      <Fragment slot="nav">
        <AboutNav />
      </Fragment>
    </PageHero>

    <div class="about-body prose">
      <p>
        This website is built using <a
          href="https://astro.build"
          target="_blank">Astro</a
        >, and I have to say I'm really enjoying it. It's a great tool for
        building static sites, and it's really easy to use. I can write my blog
        and reading content in Markdown, and Astro takes care of the rest. It's
        also really fast, which is great for SEO and user experience.
      </p>
      <p>
        Each push to the main branch of it's <a
          href="https://github.com/neilmerton/neilmerton.github.io"
          target="_blank">repository</a
        > triggers a build on Vercel, which then deploys the site. It's a great workflow,
        and it means that I can make changes to the site and see them live in seconds.
      </p>
      <p>
        I've not used a utility CSS framework for my site. I prefer to write my
        CSS using plain old CSS, and I find that it works well for me. I can
        create classes and keep my styling and presentation separate, which is
        important to me. I also find that I can compose pure CSS much quicker
        than constantly having to remember what the utility framework's class
        might be to achieve the style I'm after.
      </p>
      <p>
        There's no cookies or tracking on this site. I value my privacy, and
        that of my visitors, and I don't want to collect any data on them. I
        also don't want to have to deal with the legal implications of
        collecting data, so it's just easier to not do it at all.
      </p>
      <footer>
        <hr />
        <p><a href="/about">← Back to About</a></p>
      </footer>
    </div>
  </article>
</Layout>
